And using those, I can estimate
that if you wanted to go down

00:36:54.540 --> 00:36:57.560 align:middle line:84%
a gigaton of carbon, you'd
need to plant a seaweed

00:36:57.560 --> 00:36:59.840 align:middle line:84%
farm around the size
of South Australia,

00:36:59.840 --> 00:37:02.480 align:middle line:90%
a million square kilometers.

00:37:02.480 --> 00:37:04.580 align:middle line:84%
If you wanted to offset
all of human emissions,

00:37:04.580 --> 00:37:06.080 align:middle line:84%
so draw down all
of the carbon we're

00:37:06.080 --> 00:37:08.450 align:middle line:84%
putting in the atmosphere,
you'd need a seaweed

00:37:08.450 --> 00:37:09.750 align:middle line:90%
farm the size of Asia.

00:37:09.750 --> 00:37:13.900 align:middle line:84%
That would be 9% of the world's
ocean covered in seaweed farms.

00:37:13.900 --> 00:37:16.650 align:middle line:84%
I don't think I'm going to
see that in my lifetime.

00:37:16.650 --> 00:37:18.650 align:middle line:84%
But I do think it's
realistic to look

00:37:18.650 --> 00:37:22.170 align:middle line:84%
at covering 1% of the world's
ocean in seaweed farms.

00:37:22.170 --> 00:37:24.970 align:middle line:84%
And if we did that,
we'd be pulling down

00:37:24.970 --> 00:37:28.250 align:middle line:84%
5 gigatons of carbon
a year, and that

00:37:28.250 --> 00:37:30.830 align:middle line:84%
would be an enormous
help in terms

00:37:30.830 --> 00:37:32.170 align:middle line:90%
of addressing climate change.

00:37:32.170 --> 00:37:35.760 align:middle line:90%


00:37:35.760 --> 00:37:38.310 align:middle line:84%
Every year, we put
about 50 gigatons--

00:37:38.310 --> 00:37:40.890 align:middle line:90%
that's 50 billion tons--

00:37:40.890 --> 00:37:44.130 align:middle line:84%
of carbon dioxide or
equivalent into the atmosphere,

00:37:44.130 --> 00:37:47.610 align:middle line:90%
where it causes climate change.

00:37:47.610 --> 00:37:51.260 align:middle line:84%
But seaweed can draw this
carbon out of the atmosphere.

00:37:51.260 --> 00:37:54.720 align:middle line:84%
Five gigatons would make
a noticeable difference.

00:37:54.720 --> 00:37:57.730 align:middle line:90%
20 would make a big one.

00:37:57.730 --> 00:37:59.680 align:middle line:84%
But if seaweeds
are going to help,

00:37:59.680 --> 00:38:02.940 align:middle line:84%
we need to grow them
in the open ocean.

00:38:02.940 --> 00:38:04.770 align:middle line:90%
And there's a snag.

00:38:04.770 --> 00:38:09.640 align:middle line:84%
Seaweeds photosynthesis
using the sun's energy,

00:38:09.640 --> 00:38:11.775 align:middle line:90%
but they also need nutrients.

00:38:11.775 --> 00:38:14.220 align:middle line:84%
And in the open
ocean, the nutrients

00:38:14.220 --> 00:38:16.670 align:middle line:84%
are down too deep for the
seaweeds to reach them.

00:38:16.670 --> 00:38:19.540 align:middle line:90%


00:38:19.540 --> 00:38:22.690 align:middle line:84%
Growing seaweed in the
ocean will take great feats

00:38:22.690 --> 00:38:25.170 align:middle line:90%
of marine engineering.

00:38:25.170 --> 00:38:27.640 align:middle line:84%
But scientists and
engineers are starting

00:38:27.640 --> 00:38:29.560 align:middle line:90%
to work on the problem.

00:38:29.560 --> 00:38:32.480 align:middle line:84%
I've just came across this
rather extraordinary proposal.

00:38:32.480 --> 00:38:35.512 align:middle line:84%
It's being funded in part by the
Australian federal government.

00:38:35.512 --> 00:38:37.220 align:middle line:84%
And it concerns the
development of what's

00:38:37.220 --> 00:38:41.180 align:middle line:84%
called a marine permaculture
array in the Indian Ocean.

00:38:41.180 --> 00:38:44.430 align:middle line:84%
Now, that array will consist
of a 100-meters-squared grid

00:38:44.430 --> 00:38:47.870 align:middle line:84%
that will be used to grow
seaweed and other seafood.

00:38:47.870 --> 00:38:50.600 align:middle line:84%
What's amazing about it is it'll
be operating in the deep ocean.

00:38:50.600 --> 00:38:52.210 align:middle line:84%
It won't be tethered
to the bottom.

00:38:52.210 --> 00:38:54.240 align:middle line:90%
It will be guided by satellites.

00:38:54.240 --> 00:38:56.300 align:middle line:84%
And out there in the
deep ocean, there's

00:38:56.300 --> 00:38:59.420 align:middle line:84%
no seaweed growing now
because there's no nutrients.

00:38:59.420 --> 00:39:01.820 align:middle line:84%
So whoever's put this
together has found a way

00:39:01.820 --> 00:39:04.760 align:middle line:84%
to access those deep nutrients
and feed the seaweeds

00:39:04.760 --> 00:39:07.400 align:middle line:90%
in these permaculture arrays.

00:39:07.400 --> 00:39:10.730 align:middle line:84%
To find out just how they're
pulling up the nutrients,

00:39:10.730 --> 00:39:15.200 align:middle line:84%
I'm speaking to the man behind
the plan, eco-entrepreneur Dr.

00:39:15.200 --> 00:39:16.195 align:middle line:90%
Brian Von Herzen.

00:39:16.195 --> 00:39:17.370 align:middle line:90%


00:39:17.370 --> 00:39:20.180 align:middle line:10%
On our marine permaculture,
we run a long pipe

00:39:20.180 --> 00:39:23.450 align:middle line:10%
down several hundred
meters into the sea.

00:39:23.450 --> 00:39:24.820 align:middle line:10%
That's where the nutrients are.

00:39:24.820 --> 00:39:27.230 align:middle line:10%
And we pump them
up to the seaweed

00:39:27.230 --> 00:39:30.890 align:middle line:10%
with a combination of wind,
and wave, and solar power.

00:39:30.890 --> 00:39:33.080 align:middle line:10%
We're estimating that for
an investment of around $5

00:39:33.080 --> 00:39:37.070 align:middle line:10%
million, we can see a potential
for yields of $1 million

00:39:37.070 --> 00:39:39.410 align:middle line:10%
for the kelp biomass,
and another million

00:39:39.410 --> 00:39:41.090 align:middle line:10%
every year for the fish.

00:39:41.090 --> 00:39:42.495 align:middle line:90%
>> Wow, fantastic.

00:39:42.495 --> 00:39:43.870 align:middle line:84%
And tell me, how
long is it going

00:39:43.870 --> 00:39:46.340 align:middle line:90%
to take to get this operational?

00:39:46.340 --> 00:39:49.300 align:middle line:10%
>> Well, we're expecting this
system to be operational later

00:39:49.300 --> 00:39:50.100 align:middle line:10%
this year.

00:39:50.100 --> 00:39:52.430 align:middle line:10%
We're testing the
hardware out this summer

00:39:52.430 --> 00:39:54.340 align:middle line:10%
in Woods Hole, Massachusetts.

00:39:54.340 --> 00:39:57.570 align:middle line:10%
And we're hoping to deploy the
system next year in Australia

00:39:57.570 --> 00:39:58.550 align:middle line:10%
with further support.

00:39:58.550 --> 00:40:00.980 align:middle line:84%
>> Wow, so the first one's
only a few months off.

00:40:00.980 --> 00:40:02.075 align:middle line:90%
That's amazing.

00:40:02.075 --> 00:40:03.117 align:middle line:10%
>> Oh, thank you so much.

00:40:03.117 --> 00:40:03.917 align:middle line:10%
>> Yeah.

00:40:03.917 --> 00:40:06.320 align:middle line:84%
And you know, I really think
that you're on to something

00:40:06.320 --> 00:40:08.910 align:middle line:84%
very fundamental here,
and something very big.

00:40:08.910 --> 00:40:10.570 align:middle line:90%
So congratulations.

00:40:10.570 --> 00:40:12.710 align:middle line:84%
I can hardly wait to
see how it develops.

00:40:12.710 --> 00:40:13.798 align:middle line:90%
>> Thank you, Tim.

00:40:13.798 --> 00:40:16.190 align:middle line:90%
