00:40:16.190 --> 00:40:18.860 align:middle line:84%
I'll be interested to see
how Brian's technology copes

00:40:18.860 --> 00:40:24.260 align:middle line:84%
in the open ocean, and whether
it can deliver a result.

00:40:24.260 --> 00:40:26.900 align:middle line:84%
Brian believes that his
array should scale up

00:40:26.900 --> 00:40:31.460 align:middle line:84%
to seaweed farms a
square kilometer in size.

00:40:31.460 --> 00:40:33.830 align:middle line:84%
And to draw down a
billion tons of carbon

00:40:33.830 --> 00:40:36.830 align:middle line:84%
from the atmosphere every
year, you'd need a million

00:40:36.830 --> 00:40:40.970 align:middle line:84%
of those farms floating in
the world's oceans, growing

00:40:40.970 --> 00:40:44.470 align:middle line:90%
fish and capturing carbon.

00:40:44.470 --> 00:40:49.360 align:middle line:84%
It'll be ambitious, challenging,
and certainly expensive.

00:40:49.360 --> 00:40:53.950 align:middle line:84%
And this plan makes
one big assumption,

00:40:53.950 --> 00:40:57.040 align:middle line:84%
that all the seaweed will
sink to the ocean bottom

00:40:57.040 --> 00:40:58.810 align:middle line:84%
where it stays
out of harm's way.

00:40:58.810 --> 00:41:01.500 align:middle line:90%


00:41:01.500 --> 00:41:03.990 align:middle line:84%
I'm meeting a
scientist with doubts,

00:41:03.990 --> 00:41:08.010 align:middle line:84%
an expert in how carbon is
stored, not in the ocean

00:41:08.010 --> 00:41:09.660 align:middle line:90%
but in wetlands.

00:41:09.660 --> 00:41:11.730 align:middle line:84%
And he's not so sure the
deep ocean will easily

00:41:11.730 --> 00:41:16.320 align:middle line:84%
store the carbon from seaweed,
sometimes called macroalgae.

00:41:16.320 --> 00:41:19.680 align:middle line:84%
How do you feel about
this potential opportunity

00:41:19.680 --> 00:41:20.850 align:middle line:90%
for seaweed farming?

00:41:20.850 --> 00:41:24.800 align:middle line:84%
If we take this seaweed and
sink it into the deep ocean,

00:41:24.800 --> 00:41:27.660 align:middle line:84%
is that carbon going to stay
there effectively forever?

00:41:27.660 --> 00:41:29.810 align:middle line:84%
>> I've got some
reservations, admittedly.

00:41:29.810 --> 00:41:32.317 align:middle line:10%
Does it end up going
into the sediments,

00:41:32.317 --> 00:41:34.650 align:middle line:10%
and does it end up getting
preserved in those sediments?

00:41:34.650 --> 00:41:36.200 align:middle line:10%
I think that's the
big research gap.

00:41:36.200 --> 00:41:37.000 align:middle line:90%
>> Right.

00:41:37.000 --> 00:41:39.780 align:middle line:84%
>> I want to see some research
and data that we see that

00:41:39.780 --> 00:41:42.030 align:middle line:84%
macroalgae end up in
those deep sea areas.

00:41:42.030 --> 00:41:43.350 align:middle line:90%
But does something munch it up?

00:41:43.350 --> 00:41:44.210 align:middle line:90%
>> Fair enough.

00:41:44.210 --> 00:41:47.690 align:middle line:84%
If seaweed is munched up before
it gets to the deep ocean,

00:41:47.690 --> 00:41:52.140 align:middle line:84%
its carbon can return
to the atmosphere.

00:41:52.140 --> 00:41:56.120 align:middle line:84%
So it needs to reach the
deep ocean fast, or be buried

00:41:56.120 --> 00:41:59.240 align:middle line:84%
in ocean sediments where it's
safe from the microbes that

00:41:59.240 --> 00:42:01.520 align:middle line:90%
munch it up.

00:42:01.520 --> 00:42:04.040 align:middle line:84%
Sediments are a
natural carbon store,

00:42:04.040 --> 00:42:08.980 align:middle line:84%
and Peter shows me how
they work in mangrove mud.

00:42:08.980 --> 00:42:11.240 align:middle line:84%
>> The microbes just can't
really attack the carbon,

00:42:11.240 --> 00:42:13.922 align:middle line:84%
so it's the perfect place
to store our carbon.

00:42:13.922 --> 00:42:15.380 align:middle line:84%
>> And the bottom
of the core here,

00:42:15.380 --> 00:42:17.240 align:middle line:90%
how old do you think this is?

00:42:17.240 --> 00:42:19.627 align:middle line:84%
>> Look, if we have one
centimeter a year of accretion,

00:42:19.627 --> 00:42:21.210 align:middle line:84%
let's say that's
about 60 centimeters,

00:42:21.210 --> 00:42:23.300 align:middle line:84%
so maybe 60 years
old, about that.

00:42:23.300 --> 00:42:25.550 align:middle line:84%
>> So that carbon really
has been safely stored there

00:42:25.550 --> 00:42:27.110 align:middle line:84%
for as long as I've
been alive, anyway.

00:42:27.110 --> 00:42:27.910 align:middle line:90%
>> That's right.

00:42:27.910 --> 00:42:30.050 align:middle line:84%
>> Well, that is
very convincing.

00:42:30.050 --> 00:42:32.570 align:middle line:84%
In this mangrove
mud, it's too cold,

00:42:32.570 --> 00:42:34.970 align:middle line:84%
and there's not enough
oxygen for the microbes

00:42:34.970 --> 00:42:37.550 align:middle line:84%
to munch up the
carbon stored here.

00:42:37.550 --> 00:42:40.970 align:middle line:84%
>> And these ecosystems will
store the carbon in the ground

00:42:40.970 --> 00:42:42.360 align:middle line:90%
for thousands of years.

00:42:42.360 --> 00:42:44.155 align:middle line:84%
They retire it from
the carbon cycle,

00:42:44.155 --> 00:42:45.530 align:middle line:84%
grabbing it out
of the atmosphere

00:42:45.530 --> 00:42:46.822 align:middle line:90%
and putting it into the ground.

00:42:46.822 --> 00:42:49.940 align:middle line:84%
It's a watery grave,
and it'll stay there.

00:42:49.940 --> 00:42:53.070 align:middle line:84%
>> Mangroves are clearly a
great place to store carbon,

00:42:53.070 --> 00:42:55.940 align:middle line:84%
but they're relatively
few in number.

00:42:55.940 --> 00:42:58.970 align:middle line:84%
To store all the carbon we need
to draw out of the atmosphere,

00:42:58.970 --> 00:43:02.210 align:middle line:90%
something much bigger is needed.

00:43:02.210 --> 00:43:06.360 align:middle line:90%
So can the deep oceans do it?

00:43:06.360 --> 00:43:08.640 align:middle line:90%
The answers won't come easily.

00:43:08.640 --> 00:43:14.020 align:middle line:84%
The deep ocean is more alien
than anything on Earth.

00:43:14.020 --> 00:43:16.470 align:middle line:84%
But if seaweed gets
into the deep ocean,

00:43:16.470 --> 00:43:19.710 align:middle line:90%
there should be evidence of it.

00:43:19.710 --> 00:43:23.640 align:middle line:84%
One team has scoured deep sea
surveys from around the world,

00:43:23.640 --> 00:43:26.310 align:middle line:84%
and they think
there is evidence.

00:43:26.310 --> 00:43:31.170 align:middle line:10%
>> And we were surprised to
find many records of seaweeds

00:43:31.170 --> 00:43:33.540 align:middle line:10%
in the deep ocean, on
the deep sea floor,

00:43:33.540 --> 00:43:35.860 align:middle line:10%
several thousand meters down.

00:43:35.860 --> 00:43:39.990 align:middle line:10%
So not only are they able to
be exported there, but also

00:43:39.990 --> 00:43:43.350 align:middle line:10%
